---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Methodology & Sources | STRLaws"
  description="How STRLaws sources, verifies, and updates short-term rental regulation data across the United States."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 prose">
    <h1 class="text-h1 font-wordmark text-navy mb-6">Methodology &amp; Sources</h1>

    <h2 class="text-h2 text-navy mt-8">Where regulation data comes from</h2>
    <p class="text-ink-2">
      STRLaws scrapes municipal code repositories, city council minutes, state legislative
      records, and short-term rental program portals for each tracked jurisdiction.
      Primary sources are linked directly from every city page.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-h2 text-navy mt-8">How extractions are verified</h2>
    <p class="text-ink-2">
      Each scrape is processed by an AI extraction pipeline (Claude — Anthropic) that
      produces a structured record with a self-reported confidence score. Extractions
      below 85% confidence are routed to human review before publication. Extractions
      above 85% publish automatically and are re-verified on the next weekly scrape.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-h2 text-navy mt-8">Update cadence</h2>
    <p class="text-ink-2">
      Every tracked city is re-scraped weekly. Changes are diffed against the previous
      verified state and classified as <em>minor</em>, <em>material</em>, or <em>major</em>.
      Material and major changes trigger blog posts and subscriber alerts.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-h2 text-navy mt-8">Not legal advice</h2>
    <p class="text-ink-2">
      STRLaws is an information service. The data here is curated for general guidance,
      not legal opinion. Always verify regulations directly with the issuing municipality
      and consult a qualified attorney before making compliance-sensitive decisions.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
